(1179, 50, 'p2', 'Who chairs the debates in the House of Commons?', 'radio', 'Debates in the House of Commons are chaired bythe Speaker.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1180, 50, 'p3', 'The Battle of Hastings is commemorated in a great piece of embroidery, which is known as:', 'radio', 'The Battle of Hastings is commemorated in a great piece of embroidery, known asthe Bayeux tapestry, which can still be seen in France today.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1181, 50, 'p4', 'A woman who is violent towards her partner cannot be prosecuted in the UK:', 'radio', 'False. Anyone who is violent towards their partner – whether they are a man or a woman, married or living together – can be prosecuted.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1182, 50, 'p5', 'According to the 2011 census, what percentage of the population identified themselves as Christian?', 'radio', 'According to the 2011 Census,59%of people identified themselves as Christians.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1183, 50, 'p6', 'Many MPs, SMs and MSPs hold regular local events where constituents can go in person to talk about issues that are of concern to them. These are known as:', 'radio', 'Many MPs, SMs and MSPs  hold regularlocal ‘surgeries’, where constituents can go in person to talk about issues that are of concern to them. These surgeries are often advertised in the local newspaper.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1184, 50, 'p7', 'Which golf ‘Major’ tournament is hosted by a different golf course every year?', 'radio', 'The open championshipis the only ‘Major’ tournament held outside United States. It is hosted by a different golf course every year.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1185, 50, 'p8', 'Which act introduced the Forced Marriage Protection Orders for England, Wales and Northern Ireland in 2008?', 'radio', 'Forced Marriage Protection Orders were introduced in 2008 for England, Wales and Northern Ireland underthe Forced Marriage (Civil Protection) Act 2007. Similar Protection Orders were introduced in Scotland in November 2011.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1186, 50, 'p9', 'Which of the following countries did NOT join the European Economic Community when it was first formed in 1957?', 'radio', 'West Germany, France, Belgium, Italy, Luxembourg and the Netherlands formed the European Economic Community (EEC) in 1957. At firstthe UKdid not wish to join the EEC but it eventually did so in 1973.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1187, 50, 'p10', 'How many members does the Northern Ireland assembly have?', 'radio', 'The Northern Ireland Assembly has90 elected members, known as MLAs (members of the Legislative Assembly). They are elected with a form of proportional representation.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1188, 50, 'p11', 'Which of the following civil laws include disputes between landlords and tenants over issues such as repairs and eviction?', 'radio', 'Housing lawincludes disputes between landlords and tenants over issues suck as repairs and eviction.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1189, 50, 'p12', 'How can you visit the Scottish Parliament?', 'radio', 'To visit the Scottish Parliament, you can get information, book tickets or arrange tours through visitor services. You can also write to them at the Scottish Parliament, Edinburgh, EH99 1SP, telephone 0131 348 5200 or email sp.booking@scottish.parliament.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1190, 50, 'p13', 'Which of the following gardens is located in Wales?', 'radio', 'There are famous gardens to visit throughout the UK, including Kew Gardens, Sissinghurst and Hidcote in England, Crathes Castle and Inveraray Castle in Scotland,Bodnant Gardenin Wales, and Mount Stewart in Northern Ireland.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1191, 50, 'p14', 'Who was reining in Britain when the British Empire became the largest empire the world has ever seen, with an estimated population of more than 400 million people?', 'radio', 'During the Victorian period, the British Empire grew to cover all of India, Australia and large parts of Africa. It became the largest empire the world has ever seen, with an estimated population of more than 400 million people.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1192, 50, 'p15', 'Which of the following is NOT a duty of the police?', 'radio', 'The job of the police in the UK is to protect life and property, prevent disturbances (also known as keeping the peace) and prevent and detect crime.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1193, 50, 'p16', 'The UK is not part of which of the following international institutions?', 'radio', 'The UK is a member of the Council of Europe, the United Nations and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO). The UK is no longer a member of the European Union.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1194, 50, 'p17', 'Where is the National Gallery of Scotland located?', 'radio', 'The National Gallery of Scotland isin Edinburgh.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1195, 50, 'p18', 'Where are the ancestors of the first farmers to arrive in Britain believed to come from?', 'radio', 'The first farmers arrived in Britain 6,000 years ago. The ancestors of these first farmers probably came fromsouth-east Europe.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1196, 50, 'p19', 'What religion did Elizabeth I follow?', 'radio', 'Queen Elizabeth I was aProtestant.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1197, 50, 'p20', 'Who directed the movie ‘Chariots of Fire’ in 1981?', 'radio', 'Chariots of Fire (1981) was directed byHugh Hudson.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1198, 50, 'p21', 'What do new citizens have to swear or affirm as part of the citizenship ceremony?', 'radio', 'New citizens swear or affirmloyalty to the Kingas part of the citizenship ceremony.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1199, 50, 'p22', 'In which TWO cases may a person who has been summoned to do jury service be exempted from doing it:', 'checkbox', 'Everyone who is summoned to do jury service must do it unless they are not eligible (for example, because they have a criminal conviction) or they provide a good reason to be excused, such as ill health.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1200, 50, 'p23', 'What is the role of the shadow cabinet?', 'radio', 'Incorrect The role of the shadow cabinet is to challenge the government and put forward alternative policies.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1201, 51, 'p0', 'Which hill fort from the Iron Age can be seen in the county of Dorset?', 'radio', 'A very impressive hill fort from the Iron Age can still be seen today atMaiden Castle, in the English county of Dorset.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1202, 51, 'p1', 'On which of the following issues the Northern Ireland Assembly CANNOT make decisions?', 'radio', 'The Northern Ireland Assembly can make decisions on issues such as education, agriculture, the environment, health and social services.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1203, 51, 'p2', 'Who was the first person to sail single-handed around the world in 1966/67?', 'radio', 'A British sailor,Sir Francis Chichester, was the first person to sail singlehanded around the world, in 1966/67.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1204, 51, 'p3', 'In 1837, Queen Victoria became queen of the UK at the age of 20.', 'radio', 'In 1837, Queen Victoria became queen of the UKat the age of 18.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1205, 51, 'p4', 'Who led the group of Catholics who tried to kill the Protestant king with a bomb in the Houses of the Parliament in 1605?', 'radio', 'In 1605, a group of Catholics led byGuy Fawkesfailed in their plan to kill the Protestant king with a bomb in the Houses of Parliament. This is the origin of the Bonfire Night celebration on the 5th November, when people in Great Britain set off fireworks at home or in special displays.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1206, 51, 'p5', 'What was the biggest source of employment in Britain before the 18th century?', 'radio', 'Before the 18th century,agriculturewas the biggest source of employment in Britain.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1207, 51, 'p6', 'In which city is the Scottish Parliament building, also known as Holyrood, located?', 'radio', 'In Scotland the elected members, called MSPs, meet in the Scottish Parliament building at Holyrood inEdinburgh.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1208, 51, 'p7', 'The UK continues to be a world leader in the development and manufacture of motor-sport technology:', 'radio', 'There is a long history of motor sport in the UK, for both cars and motor cycles. Motor-car racing in the UK started in 1902. The UK continues to be a world leader in the development and manufacture of motor-sport technology.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1209, 51, 'p8', 'Why was the ‘Habeas Corpus Act’ of 1679 an important piece of legislation?', 'radio', 'The Habeas Corpus Act became law in 1679. This was a very important piece of legislation which remains relevant today. The Act guaranteed that no one could be held prisoner unlawfully. Every prisoner has a right to a court hearing.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1210, 51, 'p9', 'What British artist was awarded the Turner Prize?', 'radio', 'Damien Hirst.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1211, 51, 'p10', 'How many members has the Council of Europe?', 'radio', 'The Council of Europe is separated from the EU. It has47 member countries, including the UK, and is responsible for the protection and promotion of human rights in those countries.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1212, 51, 'p11', 'In the UK, Members of the Parliament (MPs) are elected on the basis of:', 'radio', 'MPs are elected through a system called‘first past the post’. In  constituency, the candidate who gets the most votes is elected.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1213, 51, 'p12', 'Which of the following statements regarding television in Northern Ireland is TRUE?', 'radio', 'There are programmes specific to Northern Ireland and some programmes broadcast in Irish Gaelic.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44');
INSERT INTO `questions` (`id`, `test_id`, `question_id`, `question_text`, `question_type`, `explanation`, `created_at`) VALUES
(1214, 51, 'p13', 'In the second half of the 19th century there was an important group of artists who painted detailed pictures on religious or literary themes in bright colours. These were known as:', 'radio', 'The Pre-Raphaeliteswere an important group of artists in the second half of the 19th century. They painted detailed pictures on religious or literary themes in bright colours. The group included Holman Hunt, Dante Gabriel Rossetti and Sir John Millais.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1215, 51, 'p14', 'The Muslim festival known as Eid ul Adha reminds Muslims of their own commitment to God:', 'radio', 'Eid ul Adha reminds Muslims of their own commitment to God.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1216, 51, 'p15', 'What was the population of the UK in 1901?', 'radio', 'The population of the UK in 1901 was40 million people.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1217, 51, 'p16', 'People in the UK do NOT have to pay tax on:', 'radio', 'People in the UK have to pay tax on their income, which includes: wages from paid employment, profits from self-employment, taxable benefits, pensions and income from property, savings and dividends.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1218, 51, 'p17', 'Which British scientist co-invented the MRI (magnetic resonance imaging) scanner?', 'radio', 'Sir Peter Mansfield(1933-), a British scientist, is the co-inventor of the MRI (magnetic resonance imaging) scanner. This enables doctors and researchers to obtain exact and non-invasive images of human internal organs and has revolutionised diagnostic medicine.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1219, 51, 'p18', 'Which political party called a referendum on the UK’s membership of the European Union?', 'radio', 'The Conservative governmentcalled a referendum on the UK’s membership of the European Union.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1220, 51, 'p19', 'Which of the following is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and a popular area for walkers?', 'radio', 'Parts ofHadrian’s Wall, including the forts of Housesteads and Vindolanda is a popular area for walkers and is a UNESCO (United Nations Educational Scientific and Cultural Organization) World Heritage Site.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1221, 51, 'p20', 'When did hereditary peers lose the automatic right to attend the House of Lords?', 'radio', 'Since1999, hereditary peers have lost the automatic right to attend the House of Lords. They now elect a few of their number to represent them in the House of Lords.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1222, 51, 'p21', 'Which charity works for the preservation of buildings in England?', 'radio', 'In the UK, many parts of the countryside and places of interest are kept open bythe National Trustin England, Wales and Northern Ireland and the National Trust for Scotland. Both are charities that work to preserve important buildings, coastline and countryside in the UK.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1223, 51, 'p22', 'What name is given to the new social classes that appeared after the Black Death plague and who owned large areas of land?', 'radio', 'Following the Black Death, the smaller population meant there was less need to grow cereal crops. There were labour shortages and peasants began to demand higher wages. New social classes appeared, including owners of large areas of land (later calledthe gentry), and people left the countryside to live in the towns. In the towns, growing wealth led to the development of a strong middle class.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1224, 51, 'p23', 'Which of the following is a traditional Welsh food?', 'radio', 'Welsh cakesare a traditional Welsh snack made from flour, dried fruits and spices, and served either hot or cold.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1225, 52, 'p0', 'Which of the following was one of the most famous battles of the Hundred Years War?', 'radio', 'One of the most famous battles of the Hundred Years War wasthe Battle of Agincourtin 1415, where King Henry V’s vastly outnumbered English army defeated the French. The English left France in the 1450s.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1226, 52, 'p1', 'During the Middle Ages, England was an important trading nation and people came to England from abroad to trade and also to work. Where did the engineers come from?', 'radio', 'During the Middle Ages, people came to England from abroad to trade and also to work. Many had special skills, such as weavers from France, engineers fromGermany, glass manufacturers from Italy and canal builders from Holland.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1227, 52, 'p2', 'Who was the captain of the English football team that won the World Cup in 1966?', 'radio', 'Bobby Moore(1941-93) captained the English football team that won the World Cup in 1966.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1228, 52, 'p3', 'Membership to the Commonwealth  is compulsory for its members:', 'radio', 'Membership to the Commonwealth is voluntary.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1229, 52, 'p4', 'How many verdicts are possible in trials in Scotland?', 'radio', 'The jury has to listen to the evidence presented at the trial and then decide a verdict of ‘guilty’ or ‘not guilty’ based of what they have heard. In Scotland, a third verdict of ‘not proven’ is also possible.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1230, 52, 'p5', 'How many wives did Henry VIII have?', 'radio', 'Henry VIII hadsix wives.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1231, 52, 'p6', 'Which of the following charities works with sick animals?', 'radio', 'ThePDSAis the People’s Dispensary for Sick Animals.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1232, 52, 'p7', 'Which of the following is the responsibility of the Home Secretary?', 'radio', 'The Home Secretary is responsible forcrime, policing and immigration.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1233, 52, 'p8', 'Which of the following sports can be traced as far back as the Roman times?', 'radio', 'There is a very long history ofhorse racingin Britain, with evidence of events taking place as far back as Roman times.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1234, 52, 'p9', 'When did the English become the preferred language of the royal court and Parliament?', 'radio', 'By1400, in England, official documents were being written in English, and English had become the preferred language of the royal court and Parliament.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1235, 52, 'p10', 'When is St Andrews Day, patron saint of Scotland?', 'radio', 'St Andrews Day, patron saint of Scotland, is celebrated on the30th of November.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1236, 52, 'p11', 'Which organisation has been organising ‘The Proms’ since 1927?', 'radio', 'The Proms is an eight-week summer season of orchestral classical music that takes place in various venues, including the Royal Albert Hall in London. It has been in various venues, including the Royal Albert Hall in London. It has been organised bythe British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC)since 1927.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1237, 52, 'p12', 'Which of the following organisations has no power to make laws but draws up conventions and charters, including the European Convention on Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms?', 'radio', 'The Council of Europeis responsible for the protection and promotion of human rights in those countries. It has no power to make laws but draws up conventions and charters, the most well-known of which is the European Convention on Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms, usually called the European Convention on Human Rights.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1238, 52, 'p13', 'Where is Snowdonia National Park located?', 'radio', 'Snowdonia is a national park inNorth Wales.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1239, 52, 'p14', 'What actions did Henry VII take after his victory in the Wars of the Roses?', 'radio', 'After his victory in the Wars of the Roses, Henry VII wanted to make sure that England remained peaceful and that his position as king was secure. He deliberately strengthened the central administration of England and reduced the power of the nobles.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1240, 52, 'p15', 'Which Court deals with the most serious civil cases in Scotland?', 'radio', 'More serious civil cases – for example, when a large amount of compensation is being claimed – are dealt with in the High Court of England, Wales and Northern Ireland. In Scotland, they are dealt with inthe Court of Sessionin Edinburgh.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1241, 52, 'p16', 'The leader of the opposition leads his or her party in pointing out what they see as the government’s (choose TWO options):', 'checkbox', 'The leader of the opposition leads his or her party in pointing out what they see asthe government’s failures and weaknesses.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1242, 52, 'p17', 'Who became Prime Minister of the UK in May 2010?', 'radio', 'In May 2010, and for the first time in the UK since February 1974, no political party won an overall majority in the General Election. The Conservative and Liberal Democrat parties formed a coalition and the leader of the Conservative Party,David Cameron, became Prime Minister.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1243, 52, 'p18', 'The Reform Act of 1832 abolished the old pocket and rotten boroughs.', 'radio', 'This statement istrue.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1244, 52, 'p19', 'What is the minimum age requirement to drive a moped in the UK?', 'radio', 'You need to be at least16years old to ride a moped, and there are other age requirements and special tests for driving large vehicles.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1245, 52, 'p20', 'Which of the following statements is true?', 'radio', 'Great Britain refers only to England, Scotland and Wales, not to Northern Ireland.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1246, 52, 'p21', 'How many countries formed the European Economic Community (EEC) when it was first created in 1957?', 'radio', 'The European Economic Community (EEC), was set up bysixwestern European countries (Belgium, France, Germany, Italy, Luxembourg and the Netherlands) who signed the Treaty of Rome on 25 March 1957.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1247, 52, 'p22', 'Northern Ireland and Wales have their own banknotes, which are valid everywhere in the UK. However, shop and businesses do not have to accept them:', 'radio', 'Northern Ireland and Scotlandhave their own banknotes, which are valid everywhere in the UK. However, shops and businesses do not have to accept them.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1248, 52, 'p23', 'What is donated blood used for?', 'radio', 'Donated blood is used by hospitalsto help people with a wide range of injuries and illnesses.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1249, 53, 'p0', 'How often are the general elections held in the UK?', 'radio', 'MPs are elected at a General Election, which is held at leastevery five years.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1250, 53, 'p1', 'Where is the Grand National horse racing event celebrated?', 'radio', 'The Grand National horse racing event is celebratedin Aintreenear Liverpool.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1251, 53, 'p2', 'What was Charles Chaplin famous for?', 'radio', 'Sir Charles (Charlie) Chaplin became famous insilent moviesfor his tramp character and was one of many British actors to make a career in Hollywood.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1252, 53, 'p3', 'What was Boudicca, the queen of the Iceni in what is now eastern England, known for?', 'radio', 'One of the tribal leaders whofought against the Romanswas Boudicca, the queen of the Iceni in what is now eastern England.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1253, 53, 'p4', 'What percentage of the British population has a parent or grandparent born outside of the UK as a result of post-war immigration?', 'radio', 'Post-war immigration means thatnearly 10% of the populationhas a parent or grandparent born outside the UK.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1254, 53, 'p5', 'When was the hovercraft invented?', 'radio', 'Sir Christopher Cockerell (1910-99), a British inventor, invented the hovercraftin the 1950s.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1255, 53, 'p6', 'Who is the author of the famous play ‘Macbeth’?', 'radio', 'Macbeth is a famous play byWilliam Shakespeare.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1256, 53, 'p7', 'What animal was cloned by scientists Sir Ian Wilmot and Keith Campbell?', 'radio', 'In 1996, two British scientists, Sir Ian Wilmot (1944-) and Keith Campbell (1954-2012), led a team which was the first to succeed in cloning a mammal, Dolly thesheep.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1257, 53, 'p8', 'What is the name of the building where the Northern Ireland Assembly meet?', 'radio', 'The Northern Ireland Assembly building is known asStormont.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1258, 53, 'p9', 'Which of the following is NOT a function of the House of Lords?', 'radio', 'The House of Lords can suggest amendments or propose new laws, which are then discussed by MPs. The House of Lords checks laws that have been passed by the House of Commons to ensure they are fit for purpose. It also holds the government to account to make sure that it is working in the best interests of the people.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1259, 53, 'p10', 'Which of the following is NOT a World Heritage Site?', 'radio', 'The London Eyeis not a World Heritage Site.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1260, 53, 'p11', 'Which famous murder-mystery play has been running in the west end since 1952 and has had the longest initial run of any show in history?', 'radio', 'The Mousetrap, a murder-mystery play by Dame Agatha Christie, has been running in the west end since 1952 and has had the longest initial run of any show in history.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1261, 53, 'p12', 'When was the Giant’s Causeway formed?', 'radio', 'The Giant’s Causeway was formed about50 million years ago.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1262, 53, 'p13', 'Who was the first person to sail single-handed around the world without stopping?', 'radio', 'A British sailor, Sir Francis Chichester, was the first person to sail singlehanded around the world, in 1966/67. Two years later,Sir Robin Knox- Johnstonbecame the first person to do this without stopping.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1263, 53, 'p14', 'What British writer created the fictional detective Sherlock Holmes?', 'radio', 'Sir Arthur Conan Doylewas a Scottish doctor and writer. He was best known for his stories about Sherlock Holmes, who was one of the first fictional detectives.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1264, 53, 'p15', 'How can you visit the  Senedd?', 'radio', 'To book guided tours or seats in the public galleries for the Senedd you cancontact the Senedd Booking Serviceon 0300 200 6565, email contact@senedd.wales or visit www.senedd.wales for an online booking form.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1265, 53, 'p16', 'How were Elizabeth I and ‘Mary, Queen of Scots’ related?', 'radio', '‘Mary, Queen of Scots’ was Elizabeth I’s cousin.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1266, 53, 'p17', 'Choose the correct answer. The Middle Ages were:', 'radio', 'The Middle Ages (or the medieval period) was a time of almostconstant war.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1267, 53, 'p18', 'What does the NATO stand for?', 'radio', 'NATO stands forThe North Atlantic Treaty Organisation.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1268, 53, 'p19', 'What characterised the people from the Bronze Age?', 'radio', 'The people of the Bronze Agewere accomplished metalworkerswho made many beautiful objects in bronze and gold, including tools, ornaments and weapons.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1269, 53, 'p20', 'Where is the National Horseracing Museum located?', 'radio', 'The National Horseracing Museum is located inNewmarket, Suffolk.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1270, 53, 'p21', 'In which of the following matters the Scottish Parliament CANNOT legislate?', 'radio', 'The matters on which the Scottish Parliament can legislate include: civil and criminal law, health, education, planning and additional tax-raising powers.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1271, 53, 'p22', 'Which of the following is a popular showcase of mainly theatre and comedy performances and the biggest and most well-known festival that takes place during the Edinburgh Festival?', 'radio', 'The Fringeis a showcase of mainly theatre and comedy performances. It often shows experimental work.The biggest and most well-known being the Edinburgh Festival Fringe.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1272, 53, 'p23', 'Does Britain have a constitutional monarchy?', 'radio', 'The UK has a constitutional monarchy.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1273, 54, 'p0', 'Who defeated the French at the battle of Agincourt in 1415?', 'radio', 'One of the most famous battles of the Hundred Years War was the Battle of Agincourt in 1415, whereKing Henry V’s vastly outnumbered English army defeated the French.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1274, 54, 'p1', 'Which is the most famous tennis tournament hosted in Britain and which takes place each year at the All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club?', 'radio', 'The most famous tournament hosted in Britain isThe Wimbledon Championships, which takes place each year at the All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1275, 54, 'p2', 'What is the minimum age required for a citizen to stand for public office?', 'radio', 'Most citizens of the UK, the Irish republic or the Commonwealth aged18or over can stand for public office.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1276, 54, 'p3', 'Who makes sure that the opposition has a guaranteed amount of time to debate issues which it chooses during political debates?', 'radio', 'The Speakerkeeps order during political debates to make sure the rules are followed. This includes making sure the opposition has a guaranteed amount of time to debate issues which it chooses.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1277, 54, 'p4', 'Citizens of Liechtenstein can drive in the UK for as long as their driving license is valid:', 'radio', 'If your driving licence if from a country in the European Union (EU), Iceland, Liechtenstein or Norway, you can drive in the UK for as long as your licence is valid.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1278, 54, 'p5', 'Which British Prime Minister nationalized major industries including coal and steel?', 'radio', 'Clement Attlee’s government undertook the nationalisation of major industries (like coal and steel), created the National Health Service and implemented many of Beveridge’s plans for a stronger welfare state. Attlee also introduced measures to improve the conditions of workers.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1279, 54, 'p6', 'Who was the first Archbishop of Canterbury?', 'radio', 'St Augustinebecame the first Archbishop of Canterbury.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1280, 54, 'p7', 'What is the money raised from the Income Tax used for (choose THREE options)?', 'checkbox', 'Money raised from income tax pays for government services such asroads, education, police and the armed forces.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1281, 54, 'p8', 'What name is given to the clock tower at the Houses of Parliament in honour of Queen Elizabeth II’s Diamond Jubilee in 2012?', 'radio', 'The clock tower at the Houses of Parliament in London is named‘Elizabeth Tower’in honour of Queen Elizabeth II’s Diamond Jubilee in 2012.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1282, 54, 'p9', 'When were the Forced Marriage Protection Orders introduced for England, Wales and Northern Ireland, which aimed at protecting a person from being forced into a marriage, or to protect a person in a forced marriage?', 'radio', 'Forced Marriage Protection Orders were introduced in2008for England, Wales and Northern Ireland under the Forced Marriage (Civil Protection) Act 2007.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1283, 54, 'p10', 'Whose details are NOT listed in the Phone Book?', 'radio', 'MPs, Senedd members (SMs) and members of the Scottish Parliament (MSPs) are also listed in The Phone Book, published by BT. The King is not.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1284, 54, 'p11', 'Which of the following words comes from the Norman French?', 'radio', 'Some words in modern English – for example, ‘park’ and‘beauty’– are based on Norman French words.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1285, 54, 'p12', 'How are the official reports where the Parliament’s proceedings are published called?', 'radio', 'Proceedings in Parliament are broadcast on television and published in official reports calledHansard.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1286, 54, 'p13', 'How many Senedd members does the Welsh government have?', 'radio', 'The Welsh government has60 Senedd members(SMs) and elections are held every four years using a form of proportional representation.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1287, 54, 'p14', 'Catherine Parr, the sixth wife of Henry VIII, was a cousin of Anne Boleyn:', 'radio', 'Catherine Howard was a cousin of Anne Boleyn.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1288, 54, 'p15', 'Who deals with cases involving personal injury, family matters, breaches of contract and divorce in Scotland?', 'radio', 'County Courts deal with a wide range of civil disputes. These include people trying to get back money that is owed to them, cases involving personal injury, family matters, breaches of contract, and divorce. In Scotland, most of these matters are dealt with inthe Sheriff Court.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1289, 54, 'p16', 'What was the symbol of York during the Wars of the Roses?', 'radio', 'The symbol of York during the Wars of the Roses wasa white rose.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1290, 54, 'p17', 'According to the 2011 Census, what percentage of the population identified themselves as Jewish?', 'radio', 'According to the 2011 Census,less than 0.5%of people identify themselves as Jewish.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1291, 54, 'p18', 'During which movement the Parliament passed laws giving women the right to equal pay and made it illegal for employees to discriminate against women because of their gender:', 'radio', 'The Swinging Sixtieswas a time when the Parliament passed new laws giving women the right to equal pay and made it illegal for employers to discriminate against women because of their gender.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1292, 54, 'p19', 'What name is given to the members of the House of Lords?', 'radio', 'Members of the House of Lords, known aspeers, are not elected by the people and do not represent a constituency.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1293, 54, 'p20', 'Where can you find a statue of Boudicca, the queen of the Iceni and one of the tribal leaders who fought against the Romans?', 'radio', 'There is a statue of Boudicca, the queen of the Iceni, onWestminster Bridgein London, near the Houses of Parliament.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1294, 54, 'p21', 'Which of the following castles is located in Scotland?', 'radio', 'Crathes Castleand Inveraray Castle are located in Scotland.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1295, 54, 'p22', 'For how long was Britain a republic under the leadership of Oliver Cromwell?', 'radio', 'Britain was a republic under the leadership of Oliver Cromwell for11 years.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1296, 54, 'p23', 'Magistrates and Justices of the Peace (JPs) are members of:', 'radio', 'Magistrates and Justices of the Peace (JPs) are members ofthe local community.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1297, 55, 'p0', 'Which British explorer mapped the coast of Australia?', 'radio', 'Captain James Cookmapped the coast of Australia and a few colonies were established there.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1298, 55, 'p1', 'How many members does a jury have in Scotland?', 'radio', 'In England, Wales and Northern Ireland a jury has 12 members, and in Scotland a jury has15 members.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1299, 55, 'p2', 'Who can get a 50% discount on their TV licences?', 'radio', 'People over 75 can apply for a free TV licence andblind peoplecan get a 50% discount.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1300, 55, 'p3', 'Which British city is famous for its celebration of Diwali?', 'radio', 'There is a famous celebration of Diwali inLeicester.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1301, 55, 'p4', 'Which of the following British actresses has NOT won an Oscar?', 'radio', 'Recent British actors to have won Oscars include Colin Firth, Sir Antony Hopkins, Dame Judi Dench, Kate Winslet and Tilda Swinton.Emily Watson has not won an oscar.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1302, 55, 'p5', 'Which of the following sports has a long association with royalty?', 'radio', 'Horse racinghas a long association with royalty.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1303, 55, 'p6', 'Hanukkah is a Jewish festival celebrated to remember the Jews’ struggle for religious freedom.', 'radio', 'Hanukkah is in November or December and is celebrated for eight days. It is to remember the Jews’ struggle for religious freedom.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1304, 55, 'p7', 'How can you visit the Northern Ireland Assembly (choose TWO options)?', 'checkbox', 'There are two ways to arrange a visit to the Northern Ireland Assembly at Stormont. You can eithercontact the Education Service(details are on the Northern Ireland Assembly website at http://www.niassembly.gov.uk)or contact an MLA.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1305, 55, 'p8', 'Most citizens of the UK, the Irish republic or the Commonwealth aged 18 or over can stand for public office, except for (choose THREE options):', 'checkbox', 'Members of the Commonwealth aged 18 or over can stand for public office. There are some exceptions, including:members of the armed forces, civil servants and people found guilty of certain criminal offences.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1306, 55, 'p9', 'What were the main occupations of the people during the Iron Age?', 'radio', 'During the Iron Age most people werefarmers, craft workers or warriors.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1307, 55, 'p10', 'To look after yourself and your family is one of the responsibilities that you will have as a permanent resident or citizen of the UK.', 'radio', 'This statement isTRUE.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1308, 55, 'p11', 'When is the electoral register updated?', 'radio', '', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1309, 55, 'p12', 'Which of the following is the official church of the state?', 'radio', 'The official Church of the state isthe Church of England(called the Anglican Church in other countries and the Episcopal Church in Scotland and the United States).', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1310, 55, 'p13', 'Where does the Scottish Parliament sit?', 'radio', 'In Scotland the elected members, called MSPs, meet in the Scottish Parliament building at Holyrood inEdinburgh.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1311, 55, 'p14', 'Who became one of the most popular monarchs in English history, particularly after 1588, when the English defeated the Spanish Armada?', 'radio', 'Elizabeth Ibecame one of the most popular monarchs in English history, particularly after 1588, when the English defeated the Spanish Armada (a large fleet of ships), which had been sent by Spain to conquer England and restore Catholicism.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1312, 55, 'p15', 'What was the population of the UK in 1700?', 'radio', 'The population of the UK in 1700 was5 million people.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1313, 55, 'p16', 'When did the ‘Concorde’ aircraft retired from service?', 'radio', '', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1314, 55, 'p17', 'When did the Allies defeat Germany marking the end of the Second World War?', 'radio', 'Following victory on the beaches of Normandy, the allied forces pressed on through France and eventually into Germany. The Allies comprehensively defeated Germanyin May 1945.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1315, 55, 'p18', 'How many square miles does Loch Lomond and the Trossachs National Park cover?', 'radio', 'Loch Lomond and the Trossachs National Park covers720 square miles(1,865 square kilometres) in the west of Scotland.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1316, 55, 'p19', 'Which British athlete won 16 medals, including 11 gold medals, in races over five Paralympic Games?', 'radio', 'Baroness Tanni Grey-Thompson(1969-) is an athlete who uses a wheelchair and won 16 Paralympic medals, including 11 gold medals, in races over five Paralympic Games. She won the London Marathon six times and broke a total of 30 world records.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1317, 55, 'p20', 'When is New Year’s Eve celebrated?', 'radio', 'New Year’s Eve is celebrated on the31st of December.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1318, 55, 'p21', 'What is the capital city of Scotland?', 'radio', 'The capital city of Scotland isEdinburgh.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1319, 55, 'p22', 'What British sportsmen holds a number of English Test cricket records?', 'radio', 'Sir Ian Botham(1955-) captained the English cricket team and holds a number of English Test cricket records, both for batting and for bowling.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1320, 55, 'p23', 'During the Middle Ages, England was an important trading nation and people came to England from abroad to trade and also to work. Where did the weavers come from?', 'radio', 'During the Middle Ages, people came to England from abroad to trade and also to work. Many had special skills, such asweavers from France, engineers from Germany, glass manufacturers from Italy and canal builders from Holland.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1321, 56, 'p0', 'What was the name of Sir Francis Drake’s ship and which was one of the first to sail around the world?', 'radio', 'Sir Francis Drake, one of the commanders in the defeat of the Spanish Armada, was one of the founders of England’s naval tradition. His ship,the Golden Hind, was one of the first to sail right around (‘circumnavigate’) the world.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1322, 56, 'p1', 'To whom do new citizens have to swear or affirm loyalty as part of the citizenship ceremony?', 'radio', 'New citizens swear or affirm loyalty tothe Kingas part of the citizenship ceremony.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1323, 56, 'p2', 'Why did Henry VIII marry Anne of Cleves?', 'radio', 'Henry married Anne of Clevesfor political reasonsbut divorced her soon after.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1324, 56, 'p3', 'How many Formula 1 Grand Prix events are held in the UK every year?', 'radio', 'A Formula 1 Grand Prix event is held in the UK each yearand a number of British Grand Prix drivers have won the Formula 1 World Championship.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1325, 56, 'p4', 'How can you visit the UK Parliament (choose TWO options)?', 'checkbox', 'To visit the UK Parliament, you can write to your local MP in advance to ask for tickets or you can Queue on the day at the public entrance.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1326, 56, 'p5', 'Forced marriage is where one or both parties do not or cannot give their consent to enter into the partnership:', 'radio', 'Forced marriage is where one or both parties do not or cannot give their consent to enter into the partnership.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1327, 56, 'p6', 'Northern Ireland and Scotland have their own banknotes, which are valid everywhere in the UK and shops and businesses are obliged to accept them:', 'radio', 'Northern Ireland and Scotland have their own banknotes, which are valid everywhere in the UK. However,shops and businesses do not have to accept them.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1328, 56, 'p7', 'How many American colonies declared their independence in 1776, stating that people had a right to establish their own governments?', 'radio', 'In 1776,13 American coloniesdeclared their independence, stating that people had a right to establish their own governments.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1329, 56, 'p8', 'Which TWO words come from the Viking language?', 'checkbox', 'Many of the Viking invaders stayed in Britain – especially in the east and north of England in an area known as the Danelaw (many place names there, such asGrimsby and Scunthorpecome from the Viking languages).', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1330, 56, 'p9', 'Which of the following drugs is NOT illegal in the UK?', 'radio', 'Drugs such as heroin, cocaine, ecstasy and cannabis are illegal in the UK.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1331, 56, 'p10', 'How is the Speaker elected?', 'radio', 'The Speaker is chosenby other MPs in a secret ballot.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1332, 56, 'p11', 'Which TWO of the following are traditional British foods?', 'checkbox', 'Roast beef and fish and chipsare traditional British foods.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1333, 56, 'p12', 'When was the Northern Ireland Parliament established for the first time?', 'radio', 'A Northern Ireland Parliament was established in1922, when Ireland was divided, but it was abolished in 1972, shortly after the Troubles broke out in 1969.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1334, 56, 'p13', 'Throughout the 1990s, Britain played a leading role in coalition forces involved in the liberation of Kuwait, following the Iraqi invasion in 1990, and the conflict in the former Republic of Yugoslavia:', 'radio', 'This statement istrue.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1335, 56, 'p14', 'The ‘swinging sixties’ was a period of significant social change and it was known for its growth in:', 'radio', 'The decade of the 1960s was a period of significant social change. It was known as the ‘swinging sixties’. There was growth inBritish fashion, cinema and popular music.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1336, 56, 'p15', 'What is the name given to the system used to deal with children and young people who have committed an offence in Scotland?', 'radio', 'In Scotland a system calledthe Children’s Hearings Systemis used to deal with children and young people who have committed an offence.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1337, 56, 'p16', 'Which prehistoric village located in northern Europe has helped archaeologists to understand more about how people live near the end of the Stone Age?', 'radio', 'Skara Braeon Orkney, off the north coast of Scotland, is the best preserved prehistoric village in northern Europe, and has helped archaeologists to understand more about how people lived near the end of the Stone Age.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1338, 56, 'p17', 'During the Middle Ages, a Parliament was developed in Scotland, which had three Houses called Estates. These were:', 'radio', 'The Parliament developed in Scotland in the Middle Ages had three Houses, called Estates:the lords, the commons and the clergy.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1339, 56, 'p18', 'Which landscape architect designed grounds around country houses so that the landscape appeared to be natural, with grass, trees and lakes?', 'radio', 'In the 18th century,Lancelot ‘Capability’ Browndesigned the grounds around country houses so that the landscape appeared to be natural, with grass, trees and lakes. He often worked with Edwin Lutyens to design colourful gardens around the houses he designed.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1340, 56, 'p19', 'Which of the following scientific discoveries helped the progress of the Industrial Revolution?', 'radio', 'Scientific discoveries, such as James Watt’s work onsteam power, helped the progress of the Industrial Revolution.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1341, 56, 'p20', 'What is the function of the UN Security Council?', 'radio', 'The UN Security Council, whichrecommends action when there are international crises and threats to peace.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1342, 56, 'p21', 'Who were the parents of Elizabeth I?', 'radio', 'Henry VIII and Anne Boleynwere the parents of Elizabeth I.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1343, 56, 'p22', 'The Isle of Man is a Crown dependency.', 'radio', 'This statement istrue.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1344, 56, 'p23', 'Which of the following charities works for the prevention of cruelty to children?', 'radio', 'TheNSPCCis the National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1345, 57, 'p0', 'How old do you need to be to buy a lottery ticket or scratch card?', 'radio', 'People under18are not allowed to participate in the National Lottery.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1346, 57, 'p1', 'Where was Catherine of Aragon (the first wife of Henry VIII) from?', 'radio', 'Catherine of Aragon was aSpanish princess.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1347, 57, 'p2', 'When did motor-car racing start in the UK?', 'radio', 'Motor-car racing in the UK started in1902.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1348, 57, 'p3', 'The Commonwealth is based on the core values of democracy, good government and the rule of law:', 'radio', 'The Commonwealth is based on the core values of democracy, good government and the rule of law.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1349, 57, 'p4', 'How long does it take to donate blood?', 'radio', 'Giving blood only takesabout an hourto do.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1350, 57, 'p5', 'When did the post-war economic boom come to an end?', 'radio', 'In the late 1970s, the post-war economic boom came to an end.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1351, 57, 'p6', 'During its government, Margaret Thatcher made structural changes to the economy through the privatisation of nationalised industries and imposed legal controls on trade union powers:', 'radio', 'Margaret Thatcher made structural changes to the economy through the privatisation of nationalised industries and imposed legal controls on trade union powers.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1352, 57, 'p7', 'Who sat at the House of Commons during the Middle Ages?', 'radio', 'In the Middle Ages, Knights, who were usually smaller landowners, and wealthy people from towns and cities were elected to sit in the House of Commons.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1353, 57, 'p8', 'Which of the following words come from the Anglo-Saxon language?', 'radio', 'The words‘Apple’ and ‘summer’are based on Anglo-Saxon words.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1354, 57, 'p9', 'Where do local authorities get funding from (choose TWO answers)?', 'checkbox', 'Local authorities provide a range of services in their areas. They are funded by moneyfrom central government and by local taxes.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1355, 57, 'p10', 'If you are self-employed:', 'radio', 'If you are self-employed,you need to pay your owntax through a system called ‘self-assessment’, which includes completing a tax return.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1356, 57, 'p11', 'What name is given to the elected members of the Northern Ireland Assembly?', 'radio', 'Members of the Northern Ireland Assembly are known asMLAs(members of the Legislative Assembly).', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1357, 57, 'p12', 'How long does the Hanukkah celebration last for?', 'radio', 'Hanukkah is in November or December and is celebrated foreight days.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1358, 57, 'p13', 'Which of the following areas did the British Empire NOT cover during the Victorian period?', 'radio', 'During the Victorian period, the British Empire grew to cover all of India, Australia and large parts of Africa.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1359, 57, 'p14', 'What percentage of the total British population is located in Wales?', 'radio', 'The total British population located in Wales isaround 5%.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1360, 57, 'p15', 'Which senior MP is responsible for issues relating to crime, policing and immigration?', 'radio', 'The Home Secretaryis responsible for crime, policing and immigration.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1361, 57, 'p16', 'Which British scientist led the development of the atomic bomb?', 'radio', 'Scientists led byErnest Rutherford, working at Manchester and then Cambridge University, were the first to ‘split the atom’ and took part in the Manhattan Project in the United States, which developed the atomic bomb.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1362, 57, 'p17', 'Which of the following movies played an important role in boosting morale during the Second World War?', 'radio', 'During the Second World War, British movies (for example,In Which We Serve) played an important part in boosting morale.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1363, 57, 'p18', 'After the Black Death, the growing wealth in the towns led to the development of a strong middle class:', 'radio', 'After the Black Death, new social classes appeared, including owners of large areas of land (later called the gentry), and people left the countryside to live in the towns. In the towns, growing wealth led to the development of a strong middle class.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1364, 57, 'p19', 'What was the ability of the Harrier jump jet aircraft?', 'radio', 'The Harrier jump jet,an aircraft capable of taking off vertically, was also designed and developed in the UK.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1365, 57, 'p20', 'Who won the 2012 Olympic gold medal in heptathlon?', 'radio', 'Jessica Ennis(1986-) won the 2012 Olympic gold medal in the heptathlon, which includes seven different track and field events. She also holds a number of British athletics records.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1366, 57, 'p21', 'What is the name of the annual cultural Welsh festival which includes music, dance, art and original performances largely in Welsh?', 'radio', 'The National Eisteddfod of Walesis an annual cultural festival which includes music, dance, art and original performances largely in Welsh. It includes a number of important competitions for Welsh poetry.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1367, 57, 'p22', 'What is the most well-known rugby league (club) competition?', 'radio', 'The Super Leagueis the most well-known rugby league (club) competition.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1368, 57, 'p23', 'Where do the Laurence Olivier Awards take place?', 'radio', 'The Laurence Olivier Awards take place annually at different venues inLondon.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1369, 58, 'p0', 'How old was the Queen of Scotland, Mary Stuart, when she became queen?', 'radio', 'The queen of Scotland, Mary Stuart (often now called ‘Mary, Queen of Scots’) was a Catholic. She was onlya week oldwhen her father died and she became queen.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1370, 58, 'p1', 'Where was the first tennis club founded?', 'radio', 'The first tennis club was founded inLeamington Spain 1872.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1371, 58, 'p2', 'Which British playwright invented many common English words and had a great influence on the English language?', 'radio', 'William Shakespearehad a great influence on the English language and invented many words that are still common today.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1372, 58, 'p3', 'In which city is the Northern Ireland Assembly building, also known as Stormont, located?', 'radio', 'The Northern Ireland Assembly building is known as Stormont and it is located inBelfast.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1373, 58, 'p4', 'What proportion of the population died as a result of the Black Death in England?', 'radio', 'As a result of the Black Death,one third of the population of England diedand a similar proportion in Scotland and Wales.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1374, 58, 'p5', 'Which famous poem tells the story of the knights at the court of King Arthur?', 'radio', 'Poems which survive from the Middle Ages include Chaucer’s Canterbury Tales and a poem calledSir Gawain and the Green Knight, about one of the knights at the court of King Arthur.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1375, 58, 'p6', 'Which of the following is NOT a fundamental principle of British life?', 'radio', 'The fundamental principles of British life include: tolerance of those with different faiths and beliefs, the rule of law, democracy, individual liberty and participation in community life.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1376, 58, 'p7', 'Which flower is associated with Northern Ireland?', 'radio', 'The shamrockis the flower associated with Northern Ireland.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1377, 58, 'p8', 'The longest distance on the mainland in the UK is from John O’Groats on the north coast of Scotland to a place in the south-west corner of England known as:', 'radio', 'The longest distance on the mainland is from John O’Groats on the north coast of Scotland toLand’s Endin the south-west corner of England. It is about 870 miles (approximately 1,400 kilometres).', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1378, 58, 'p9', 'Who wrote a famous series of poems about a group of people going to Canterbury on a pilgrimage known as ‘The Canterbury Tales’?', 'radio', 'In the years leading up to 1400,Geoffrey Chaucerwrote a series of poems in English about a group of people going to Canterbury on a pilgrimage. The people decided to tell each other stories on the journey, and the poems describe the travellers and some of the stories they told. This collection of poems is called The Canterbury Tales.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1379, 58, 'p10', 'Which of the following categories is recognised at the Laurence Olivier Awards?', 'radio', 'The Laurence Olivier Awards recognise achievements in the area oftheatre.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1380, 58, 'p11', 'In the UK, there is a National Lottery for which draws are made every day.', 'radio', 'In the UK, there is a National Lottery for which draws are madeevery week.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1381, 58, 'p12', 'Where is Europe’s longest dry ski slope located?', 'radio', 'There are five ski centres in Scotland, as well as Europe’s longest dry ski slopenear Edinburgh.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1382, 58, 'p13', 'Which TWO of Henry VIII’s wives were accused of taking lovers and executed?', 'checkbox', 'Anne Boleyn and Catherine Howardwere accused of taking lovers and executed.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1383, 58, 'p14', 'Who is the head of the state in the UK?', 'radio', 'King Charles IIIis the head of state in the UK.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1384, 58, 'p15', 'What was the population of the UK in 1600?', 'radio', 'The population of the UK in 1600 wasjust over 4 million people.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1385, 58, 'p16', 'What name is given to the 31st of December in Scotland?', 'radio', 'In Scotland, 31 December is calledHogmanay.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1386, 58, 'p17', 'In which of the following languages is the life in the UK test NOT available?', 'radio', 'The Life in the UK test is usually taken is English, although special arrangements can be made if you wish to take it in Welsh or Scottish Gaelic.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1387, 58, 'p18', 'Which two scientists were successful at cloning the first mammal, Dolly the sheep?', 'radio', 'In 1996, two British scientists,Sir Ian Wilmot and Keith Campbell, led a team which was the first to succeed in cloning a mammal, Dolly the sheep.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1388, 58, 'p19', 'When is the Sikh Vaisakhi festival celebrated?', 'radio', 'Vaisakhi (also spelled Baisakhi) is a Sikh festival which celebrates the founding of the Sikh community known as the Khalsa. It is celebrated on the14th of Aprileach year with parades, dancing and singing.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1389, 58, 'p20', 'Who were the Pre-Raphaelites?', 'radio', 'The Pre-Raphaelites werean important group of artists in the second half of the 19th century. They painted detailed pictures on religious or literary themes in bright colours. The group included Holman Hunt, Dante Gabriel Rossetti and Sir John Millais.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1390, 58, 'p21', 'When was St Pancras Station built?', 'radio', 'St Pancras Station was builtin the 19th century.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1391, 58, 'p22', 'Members of the Scottish Parliament (MSPs) are elected on the basis of:', 'radio', 'Members of the Scottish Parliament (MSPs) are elected by a form ofproportional representation.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1392, 58, 'p23', 'Which TWO of the following soap operas are popular in the UK?', 'checkbox', 'Popular programmes in the UK include regular soap operas such asCoronation Street and EastEnders.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1393, 59, 'p0', 'What does the term ‘Hansard’ relate to?', 'radio', 'Proceedings in Parliament are broadcast on television and published in official reports called Hansard.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1394, 59, 'p1', 'Who was the first king of the House of Tudor?', 'radio', 'Henry VII (Henry Tudor)was the first king of the House of Tudor.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1395, 59, 'p2', 'What do Lewis Hamilton, Jenson Button and Damon Hill have in common?', 'radio', 'Lewis Hamilton, Jenson Button and Damon Hill have won the Formula 1 World Championship.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1396, 59, 'p3', 'According to the 2011 Census, what percentage of people said that they had no religion?', 'radio', 'According to the 2011 census,25% of peoplesaid they had no religion.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1397, 59, 'p4', 'During which period were the first coins produced in Britain?', 'radio', 'The people ofthe Iron Agehad a sophisticated culture and economy. They made the first coins to be minted in Britain, some inscribed with the names of Iron Age kings.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1398, 59, 'p5', 'What other name is given to Diwali, the religious celebration that celebrates the victory of good over evil and the gaining of knowledge?', 'radio', 'Diwali normally falls in October or November and lasts for five days. It is often calledthe Festival of Lights.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1399, 59, 'p6', 'In Wales, the jury has to listen to the evidence presented at the trial and then decide a verdict of ‘guilty’, ‘not guilty’ or ‘not proven’ based of what they have heard:', 'radio', 'The jury has to listen to the evidence presented at the trial and then decide a verdict of ‘guilty’ or ‘not guilty’ based of what they have heard. In Scotland, a third verdict of ‘not proven’ is also possible.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1400, 59, 'p7', 'The Prime Minister has a country house outside London called:', 'radio', 'The Prime Minister has a country house outside London calledChequers.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1401, 59, 'p8', 'In which English county is Maiden Castle located?', 'radio', 'A very impressive hill fort can be seen today at Maiden Castle, in the English county ofDorset.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1402, 59, 'p9', 'A National Insurance number does on its own prove to an employer that you have the right to work in the UK:', 'radio', 'A National Insurance number does not on its own prove to an employer that you have the right to work in the UK.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1403, 59, 'p10', 'Which of the following is a ceremonial role to be undertaken by the King?', 'radio', 'The King has important ceremonial roles, such asthe opening of the new parliamentary session each year. On this occasion the King makes a speech which summarises the government’s policies for the year ahead.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1404, 59, 'p11', 'How long can you use your driving licence in the UK if you have a licence from another country?', 'radio', 'If you have a licence from another country, you may use it in the UKfor up to 12 months.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44');
INSERT INTO `questions` (`id`, `test_id`, `question_id`, `question_text`, `question_type`, `explanation`, `created_at`) VALUES
(1405, 59, 'p12', 'What British discovery was influential in the development of computer science and the modern-day computer?   The Radar', 'radio', 'The Turing machineis a theoretical mathematical device invented by Alan Turing (1912-54), a British mathematician, in the 1930s. The theory was influential in the development of computer science and the modern-day computer.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1406, 59, 'p13', 'Which Court deals with the serious criminal offences in England, Wales and Northern Ireland?', 'radio', 'In England, Wales and Northern Ireland, serious criminal offences are tried in front of a judge and a jury in aCrown Court.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1407, 59, 'p14', 'Which famous philosopher developed ideas about human nature during the 18th century and that have continued to influence philosophers over the years?', 'radio', 'During the 18th century,David Hume’s ideas about human nature continue to influence philosophers.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1408, 59, 'p15', 'If you are arrested and taken to a police station, a police officer should:', 'radio', 'If you are arrested and taken to a police station, a police officer willtell you the reason for your arrest and you will be able to seek legal advice.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1409, 59, 'p16', 'Which British actor has recently won an Oscar?', 'radio', 'Recent British actors to have won Oscars include Colin Firth,Sir Antony Hopkins, Dame Judi Dench, Kate Winslet and Tilda Swinton.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1410, 59, 'p17', 'What TWO names are given to the day before Lent?', 'checkbox', 'The day before Lent starts is calledShrove Tuesday, or Pancake Day.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1411, 59, 'p18', 'When did the ‘Concorde’ aircraft carry passengers for the first time?', 'radio', 'The ‘Concorde’ began carrying passengersin 1976.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1412, 59, 'p19', 'The UK is one of five permanent members of the Security Council:', 'radio', 'The UK is one of five permanent members of the Security Council.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1413, 59, 'p20', 'Which of the following landmarks is the largest expanse of fresh water in mainland Britain?', 'radio', 'Loch Lomondis the largest expanse of fresh water in mainland Britain and probably the best-known part of the park.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1414, 59, 'p21', 'Who wrote the music for the popular show Jesus Christ Superstar?', 'radio', 'Andrew Lloyd Webberhas written the music for shows which have been popular throughout the world, including, in collaboration with Tim Rice, Jesus Christ Superstar and Evita, and also Cats and The Phantom of the Opera.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1415, 59, 'p22', 'Which one of the following four changes did the Chartists did NOT campaign for?', 'radio', 'The Chartists campaigned for every man to have the vote, elections every year, for all regions to be equal in the electoral system, secret ballots, for any man to be able to stand as an MP and for MPs to be paid.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1416, 59, 'p23', 'Pantomimes are a British tradition that many theatres produce during:', 'radio', 'Many theatres produce a pantomime atChristmas time.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1417, 60, 'p0', 'How many weeks does the orchestral classical music event known as ‘the Proms’ last for?', 'radio', 'The Proms is aneight-week summer seasonof orchestral classical music that takes place in various venues, including the Royal Albert Hall in London.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1418, 60, 'p1', 'When did King Charles III start reining?', 'radio', 'The King has reigned since his mother’s death in September2022.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
