(1612, 68, 'p3', 'Who was the first person to print books using a printing press in England?', 'radio', 'William Caxtonwas the first person in England to print books using a printing press.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1613, 68, 'p4', 'In England, Wales and Scotland, most minor criminal cases are dealt with in a Magistrates’ Court:', 'radio', 'In England, Wales and Northern Ireland, most minor criminal cases are dealt with in a Magistrates’ Court. In Scotland, minor criminal offences go to a Justice of the Peace Court.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1614, 68, 'p5', 'When did the UK sign the European Convention of Human Rights?', 'radio', 'The UK was one of the first countries to sign the Convention in1950.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1615, 68, 'p6', 'Which is the most famous rugby union competition?', 'radio', 'The most famous rugby union competition isthe Six Nations Championshipbetween England, Ireland, Scotland, Wales, France and Italy.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1616, 68, 'p7', 'After Oliver Cromwell defeated the Scottish army in the Battles of Dunbar and Worcester, Charles II escaped from Worcester, famously hiding in an oak tree on one occasion, and eventually fled to Europe:', 'radio', 'This statement istrue.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1617, 68, 'p8', 'Which of the following is an ancient festival and has roots in the pagan festival to mark the beginning of winter?', 'radio', 'Halloween, 31 October, is and ancient festival and has roots in the pagan festival to mark the beginning of winter.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1618, 68, 'p9', 'Which TWO British kings believed in the ‘Divine Right of Kings’?', 'checkbox', 'James I and his son Charles Iboth believed in the ‘Divine Right of Kings’: the idea that the king was directly appointed by God to rule. They thought that the king should be able to act without having to seek approval from Parliament.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1619, 68, 'p10', 'What was the name of the European Union when it was first established?', 'radio', 'West Germany, France, Belgium, Italy, Luxembourg and the Netherlands formed theEuropean Economic Community (EEC)in 1957. The EEC became a part of the European Union when it was formed in 1993.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1620, 68, 'p11', 'By 1200, the English ruled an area of Scotland known as the Pale, around Edinburgh:', 'radio', 'By 1200, the English ruled an area of Ireland known as the Pale,around Dublin.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1621, 68, 'p12', 'Which of the following British poets was inspired by nature?', 'radio', 'William Wordsworthwas inspired by nature.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1622, 68, 'p13', 'Which Act incorporated the European Convention of Human Rights into UK law?', 'radio', 'The Human Rights Act 1998incorporated the European Convention of Human Rights into UK law.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1623, 68, 'p14', 'After the Second World War, the UK was exhausted economically.', 'radio', 'Although the UK had won the war, the country was exhausted economically after WWII.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1624, 68, 'p15', 'What percentage of the total British population is located in Northern Ireland?', 'radio', 'The population is very unequally distributed over the four parts of the UK. England more or less consistently makes up 84% of the total population, Wales around 5%, Scotland just over 8%, and Northern Irelandless than 3%.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1625, 68, 'p16', 'Bonfire Night remembers the day when a group of Catholics led by Guy Fawkes killed the Protestant king with a bomb in the Houses of Parliament:', 'radio', 'Bonfire Night remembers the day when a group of Catholics led by Guy Fawkesfailed in their plan to kill the Protestant kingwith a bomb in the Houses of Parliament.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1626, 68, 'p17', 'Who was Florence Nightingale?', 'radio', 'Florence Nightingale was a nurse who worked in military hospitals, treating soldiers who were fighting in the Crimean War.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1627, 68, 'p18', 'Where is the Scottish Grand National horse racing event celebrated?', 'radio', 'The Scottish Grand National horse racing event is celebrated atAyr.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1628, 68, 'p19', 'Arranged marriages are not acceptable in the UK:', 'radio', 'Arranged marriages, where both parties agree to the marriage,are acceptable in the UK.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1629, 68, 'p20', 'Who was the Prime Minister of the UK from 1945 to 1951?', 'radio', 'Clement Attleewas Prime Minister from 1945 to 1951 and led the Labour Party for 20 years.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1630, 68, 'p21', 'Who represents the UK to the rest of the world?', 'radio', 'The Kingrepresents the UK to the rest of the world.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1631, 68, 'p22', 'Great Britain refers only to England, Scotland and Wales, not to Northern Ireland.', 'radio', 'This statement istrue.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1632, 68, 'p23', 'Queen Elizabeth I was a Catholic:', 'radio', 'Queen Elizabeth I was aProtestant.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1633, 69, 'p0', 'What is the meaning of the term the ‘Divine Right of Kings’?', 'radio', 'The ‘Divine Right of Kings’ refers tothe idea that the king was directly appointed by God to ruleand that the king should be able to act without having to seek approval from Parliament.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1634, 69, 'p1', 'Who was the first person to lead a Roman invasion in Britain in 55 BC?', 'radio', 'Julius Caesarled a Roman invasion of Britain in 55 BC. This was unsuccessful and for nearly 100 years Britain remained separate from the Roman Empire.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1635, 69, 'p2', 'Which of the following is NOT the responsibility of the MPs?', 'radio', 'MPs have a number of different responsibilities. They represent everyone in their constituency, help to create new laws, scrutinize and comment on what the government is doing and debate important national issues.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1636, 69, 'p3', 'When Henry VIII took the title ‘King of Ireland’, English laws were introduced and everyone except for local leaders were expected to follow the instructions of the Lord Lieutenants in Dublin:', 'radio', 'When Henry VIII took the title ‘King of Ireland’, English laws were introduced andlocal leaderswere expected to follow the instructions of the Lord Lieutenants in Dublin.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1637, 69, 'p4', 'When is the anniversary of the Battle of the Boyne celebrated in Northern Ireland?', 'radio', 'In Northern Ireland, the anniversary ofthe Battle of the Boyne is celebrated in Julyand is also a public holiday.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1638, 69, 'p5', 'The clock tower is named ‘Elizabeth Tower’ in honour of ___________.', 'radio', 'The clock tower is named ‘Elizabeth Tower’ in honour ofQueen Elizabeth II’s Diamond Jubilee in 2012.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1639, 69, 'p6', 'When was Lincoln Cathedral built?', 'radio', 'Lincoln Cathedral was builtin the middle ages or medieval times.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1640, 69, 'p7', 'Which of the following territories forms part of the UK?', 'radio', 'The UK is formed byEngland, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1641, 69, 'p8', 'How old was Edward VI when he died?', 'radio', 'Edward VI died at the age of15after ruling for just over six years, and his half-sister Mary became queen.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1642, 69, 'p9', 'What name was given to those who supported the king during the Civil War that began in 1642?', 'radio', 'During the Civil War that started in 1642 those who supported the king(the Cavaliers)and those who supported Parliament (the Roundheads).', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1643, 69, 'p10', 'The right to a fair trial is not included amongst the principles of the European Convention of Human Rights:', 'radio', 'The right to a fair trialis one of the principles of the European Convention of Human Rights.', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
(1644, 69, 'p11', 'Why was Queen Mary known as ‘Bloody Mary’?', 'radio', 'Queen Mary was a devout Catholic and persecuted Protestants(for this reason, she became known as ‘Bloody Mary’).', '2025-08-02 08:38:44'),
